SENTIMENTAL JOURNEY<br>
El Toro Marine Corps Air Base<br>
El Toro, California<br>
1230 Hours, Tuesday, June 13, 1967<br><br>
My diary begins as were lined up alphabetically against a tin metal hanger at the Marine Corps Air Station in El Toro, California. Most of the 3rd Marine Aircraft Wing was located there. I looked around for a military or combat troop transport plane but saw none. Instead, on the runway, directly in front of the hanger, was a large Continental Airlines Golden Bird. It was being fueled up and would be ready for our departure at 1300 hours.    <br>
 In the three years I spent in the Corps, I never understood their fondness for starting everything at 1300 hours. The daily marching on the parade field at the Marine Corps Recruiting Depot (MCRD) in San Diego always started at 1300 hours. It was that time when we received our military orders for Vietnam and now almost six months after the date of my enlistment, my classmates and I assigned to combat duty in Viet Nam would be boarding the 707 airliner at 1300 hours. <br>
Most of us standing in line were assigned to the 1st Marine Division. It's home base was located in Camp Pendleton, California.  We all had gone through ten weeks of  basic recruit training. Some at MCRD others at Parris Island, South Carolina. All of us had completed at least an additional three months of combat or military specialty training in our Military Occupational Status (MOS) at the 1st Marine Divisions Infantry Training Regiment (ITR), at Camp Pendleton. <br>
&quot;A-ten-shun,&quot; the duty NCO in charge of the flight shouted and we snapped to. We were marched around the hanger until we were about fifty feet from the plane. <br>
&quot;D-E-T-A-I-L, Halt,&quot; the Corporal shouted and we stopped.<br>
&quot;At ease,&quot; he said, and some of us went into parade rest, while others relaxed in place. <br>
&quot;Hey, Barela, take a deep breath,&quot; Baracki said in his Texan accent, as he took in a deep breath through his wide nostrils. <br>
&quot;I don't smell anything! What do you, smell?&quot; I asked. <br>
&quot;America,&quot; he answered.<br>
&quot;Sure wish I could put this smell in a bottle and take it with me. I hear, Gooks smell like fish and the air like acid in Viet Nam.&quot; <br>
Bennet, who was standing behind Benevedo, turned his back toward us and passed gas. The sound was loud and long.<br>
&quot;Smell that,&quot; he said, and we all moved away from him.  <br>
A group of Good Samaritan civilians started walking up and down the formation. They were offering cold raspberry flavored Kool-Aid, cookies and a small pocket size New Testament Bible. Almost everyone took one of the Bibles.  No doubt on everyone's mind was the question on whether or not they would return from war, from Viet Nam.  <br>
I knew that I would return for some reason, I just knew it. I might get wounded, but I would return alive.  It was always the other guy that got killed or seriously wounded and it was always someone else who returned from war in a body bag, a dull gray casket or as a disabled veteran.  It's always someone else; someone like Baracki, who was standing in front of me, Balisher in front of him. Benevedo behind me, Bennett, Blain, Brian, Cervantez, Cincenerros, Cordavan, Cortez, it was always people like them and it was them. <br>

